But Arteta's definitive decision has not been backed up by results in his first full season in charge.
Despite an upturn in form of late inspired by the emergence of youngsters Emile Smith Rowe and Bukayo Saka, Arsenal sit eighth in the Premier League and out of both domestic cup competitions.
Even as his appearances on the field diminished under Arteta and his predecessor Unai Emery, the shadow of Ozil has continued to hang over the club.
Both Spanish coaches grew tired of the constant questions over his chances of returning to the first-team in press conferences, while Ozil's active social media presence kept him in the spotlight.
His departure offers the opportunity for Arteta and Arsenal to move on, but to do so they need results.
The economic battering from a closed stadium due to coronavirus restrictions has only deepened the Londoners' financial woes after four seasons without Champions League income.



