Yet, like many other creative talents, Odegaard has not found favour with Madrid boss Zinedine Zidane.
Isco, James Rodriguez, Gareth Bale and Odegaard's new teammate Dani Ceballos have also struggled for minutes under the Frenchman.
The fact no option to buy has been included in the deal shows the Spanish giants still rate Odegaard highly and know his future in Madrid could be much brighter when Zidane's second spell in charge comes to an end.
But he needs a stage to showcase his talent and Arsenal need another creator to compliment Saka and Smith Rowe.
Ozil's contract that became a burden is an example of how too often in recent years Arsenal have overstretched for players past their prime.
The three-year deals handed to Willian and Pierre-Emerick Aubameyang this summer already look misjudged.
Odegaard's arrival is another gamble. With Benfica to come in the Europa League last 32 next month, Arsenal's season could be over by the time he gets up to speed after months on the sidelines.
